metadata.name: Less is More #41
metadata.description:
In this case, we tried to avoid abstract expressionist tendencies by removing personal scenarios.
Take a step back and let's create a geometrical work that intentionally avoids the usual conventional elements, focusing mainly on logic and physics concepts such as mathematical expansions and gravity.
In fact, we based our work and expression on the basis of simplicity and simple methods, as well as free from the usual philosophical or pseudo-philosophical complexity, and we concluded that by using simple geometric shapes, color, form, and material can be achieved in a pure manner.
Made by p5.js
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Textura #171
metadata.description:
"Textura"

My initial goal was to create artwork that could trigger raw, visceral emotions and feelings. A polar opposite to the polite, clinical precision of some other collections, I wanted to embrace the grittier side of abstract art. 

This turned out to be a rather difficult project for me. It was a departure from my usual figurative / ink line style, where most of the time I find it straightforward to tell a "good" output from a "bad" one. Here, out of my comfort zone, I couldn't tell. I liked some outputs, I hated some. The ones I hated, usually would be someone else's favorites. Abstract art is hard !

After a while, some patterns started to emerge. The overall feedback was that, generally:
- blue outputs were peaceful
- orange ones were intense and aggressive
- black and white ones were oppressive and sometimes disturbing

If you can associate an emotion to any given output, I feel like I will have achieved my goal. Thank you to everyone who provided feedback !

 
Technically, this project also posed a number of challenges:
- how to blend a large number of procedural textures in a smooth, yet natural way
- how to make sure the final piece has some kind of depth, visible beyond the intricate layering
- how to optimize contrast and get vibrant results

This was mostly achieved by spending a lot of time designing and fine-tuning color schemes - enhanced versions of color palettes, that also contain pre and post-processing settings.

The collection features a total of 31 color schemes. 

Key commands:
'1', '2', '4': increase resolution
's': save png
'n': toggle background noise
'c': toggle background canvas texture

On mobile devices, the rendering resolution is reduced to deal with memory limitations.

metadata.name: Fractal Amoeba #430
metadata.description:
These Amoeba are moving based on mathematics fractal. These mysterious creatures fascinate us. We would lose track of time and keep looking at them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [e] to update drawing
- Press [0] to increase drawing speed
- Press [9] to decrease drawing speed
- Press [s] to save the screen to a PNG file
- Press [1],[2],[3],[4] to set pixelDensity=1,2,3,4. When you save it, the save image is 1,2,3,4 times resolution.

Create with p5.js

metadata.name: Winter Lake #12
metadata.description:
<<Anyway, il n’y avait rien, IL N’Y A RIEN tout court. Là on le voit. Là on le sait. On est tout nus dans la neige. On est vraiment un vide, un vrai vide, un qui aspire, un vacuum et ce vide garde tout le temps sa force de vide, sa faim douloureuse. Ça dévore tout à mesure, nous avec. On est un vide qui se refait, c’est ça notre sens, et on est contents. C’est pédant mais c’est ça qui est ça. On se laissera pas faire, chère, Woffe and toffe !>>  de <<L’hiver de force>> de Réjean Ducharme

A depiction of the bleakness and beauty of a Quebec winter, showing a frozen lake stretching off into the cold distance. Hints of storm clouds and the Northern Lights are visible, along with the occasional lone ice-fishing shack. L'hiver est une camisole de force...


[Vanilla javascript, with textures generated by a neural network decoder ported to javascript using ONNX Runtime Web]
